{"action": "edit", "code": "def mirror_pattern(pattern: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a pattern, mirror the finished part and return the new pattern\n    \n    Args:\n    - pattern: a tuple containing four tuples representing the coordinates of the four parts of a pattern\n    \n    Returns:\n    - a tuple containing four tuples representing the coordinates of the new pattern after mirroring\n    \"\"\"\n    finished_part = pattern[0]\n    unfinished_parts = pattern[1:]\n    new_unfinished_parts = []\n    for part in unfinished_parts:\n        new_unfinished_parts.append((2 * finished_part[0] - part[0], 2 * finished_part[1] - part[1]))\n    return (finished_part,) + tuple(new_unfinished_parts)\ndef find_patterns(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]]:\n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    Given a grid, find all the unfinished patterns, each pattern contains three or four parts, one of the parts is finished, the other three or four parts is in differe\n                                                                                                                                                                        \n    Args:                                                                                                                                                               \n    - input_grid: a numpy array representing the input grid                                                                                                             \n                                                                                                                                                                        \n    Returns:                                                                                                                                                            \n    - a list of tuples, where each tuple contains four tuples representing the coordinates of the four parts of a pattern                                               \n    \"\"\"\n    patterns = []\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] != black:\n                continue\n            neighbors = find_neighbors_in_different_color(input_grid, i, j)\n            if len(neighbors) == 3 or len(neighbors) == 4:\n                finished_part = (i, j)\n                unfinished_parts = [n for n in neighbors if input_grid[n[0]][n[1]] == black]\n                if len(unfinished_parts) == 3 or len(unfinished_parts) == 4:\n                    pattern = tuple([finished_part] + unfinished_parts)\n                    patterns.append(pattern)\n    return patterns\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    In the black grid, find the unfinish patterns, each pattern contains three or four parts, one of the parts is finished, the other three or four parts is in different colors, mirror the finished part and finished the unfinished part.                                                        \n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    patterns = find_patterns(output_grid)\n    for p in patterns:\n        output_grid = mirror_pattern(output_grid)\n    return output_grid\ndef find_neighbors_in_different_color(grid: np.ndarray, i: int, j: int) -> List[Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and a pixel with coordinates (i,j), find all its neighbors that have a different color.\n    \n    Args:\n    - grid: a numpy array representing the input grid\n    - i: an integer representing the row index of the pixel\n    - j: an integer representing the column index of the pixel\n    \n    Returns:\n    - a list of tuples, where each tuple contains two integers representing the coordinates of a neighboring pixel with a different color\n    \"\"\"\n    color = grid[i][j]\n    neighbors = []\n    if i > 0 and grid[i - 1][j] != color:\n        neighbors.append((i - 1, j))\n    if i < grid.shape[0] - 1 and grid[i + 1][j] != color:\n        neighbors.append((i + 1, j))\n    if j > 0 and grid[i][j - 1] != color:\n        neighbors.append((i, j - 1))\n    if j < grid.shape[1] - 1 and grid[i][j + 1] != color:\n        neighbors.append((i, j + 1))\n    return neighbors", "user_code": "def find_patterns(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]]:                                           \n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    Given a grid, find all the unfinished patterns, each pattern contains three or four parts, one of the parts is finished, the other three or four parts is in differe\n                                                                                                                                                                        \n    Args:                                                                                                                                                               \n    - input_grid: a numpy array representing the input grid                                                                                                             \n                                                                                                                                                                        \n    Returns:                                                                                                                                                            \n    - a list of tuples, where each tuple contains four tuples representing the coordinates of the four parts of a pattern                                               \n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    patterns = []                                                                                                                                                       \n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):                                                                                                                                \n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):                                                                                                                            \n            if input_grid[i][j] != black:                                                                                                                               \n                continue                                                                                                                                                \n            neighbors = `find neighbors pixels in different color`(input_grid, i, j)                                                                                                                        \n            if len(neighbors) == 3 or len(neighbors) == 4:                                                                                                              \n                finished_part = (i, j)                                                                                                                                  \n                unfinished_parts = [n for n in neighbors if input_grid[n[0]][n[1]] == black]                                                                            \n                if len(unfinished_parts) == 3 or len(unfinished_parts) == 4:                                                                                            \n                    pattern = tuple([finished_part] + unfinished_parts)                                                                                                 \n                    patterns.append(pattern)                                                                                                                            \n    return patterns \n    \ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:                                                                                                                         \n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    In the black grid, find the unfinish patterns, each pattern contains three or four parts, one of the parts is finished, the other three or four parts is in different colors, mirror the finished part and finished the unfinished part.                                                        \n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                                                 \n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    patterns = `find patterns`(output_grid)\n    for p in patterns:\n        output_grid = `mirror the pattern`(output_grid)                                                                                                                        \n    return output_grid ", "gpt_code": "def mirror_pattern(pattern: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a pattern, mirror the finished part and return the new pattern\n    \n    Args:\n    - pattern: a tuple cont